ECO300 | Microeconomic Theory | http://registrar.princeton.edu/course-offerings/course_details.xml?courseid=001388&term=1162 | instructors:Koen Decancq description:This is an intermediate microeconomics course. The general themes are: (1) choices made by individual consumers and firms, (2) equilibrium of the interaction of these choices in markets and (3) the role of government policy in improving economic outcomes. Some new concepts and techniques are developed, especially for studying behavior under uncertainty, and strategic interactions (game theory). The theory of each topic is accompanied by evidence, illustrations, and applications.
